The paper deals with the problem of edit similarity joins, which is a fundamental operation in data cleaning/integration, bioinformatics, and natural language processing. This suggests that the paper could belong to the database (cs.DB), data structures (cs.DS), information retrieval (cs.IR), computational linguistics (cs.CL), or computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-categories. The paper specifically mentions that edit similarity joins have been identified as a primitive operator for database systems, which makes cs.DB the most likely sub-category. However, the paper also mentions applications in bioinformatics and natural language processing, which could make cs.DS, cs.IR, or cs.CL likely sub-categories as well. Finally, the paper proposes a new algorithm that is based on metric embeddings, which could make cs.CG a possible sub-category as well.
